text: Hi Jen, I'd like to use Cloud9 IDE, it costs around $2 per month to use and requires an AWS account, can I create a new AWS account and expense it to Red Hat?
i can also use the existing AWS account instead

attachments.title: AWS Cloud9 Amazon Web Services
attachments.text: AWS Cloud9 is a cloud-based integrated development environment (IDE) that lets you write, run, and debug your code with just a browser.

text: I don’t inherently have s problem with it but I think I’d like to know more about it - is this for the work you are doing on cost management? Or something else?
it's for doing work on Cost Management.
It's an IDE, similar to VSCode, except that it works in a Browser instead of downloading it
this allows anyone to collaborate with me, on any device
I can give them a link to my IDE and they'll be able to type code as well
At least at first, it would probably be easier to use the same tools as the rest of the team. Just as you are onboarding. I think that the tool Andrew and Doug are using does the same thing.
So, I would check with Andrew first. If he doesn’t have a concern with that, then I don’t either. And ultimately I’m ok with everyone using tools they are comfortable with.
Yep, Andrew is ok with it.

"aberglun [11:23 AM]
I’m assuming the cost isn’t huge for their IDE, so I’m okay with it, but I’d just run it by Jen real quick since it is a cost thing. We have a cost management AWS account that you will need credentials for (definitely part of on-boarding) in order to really use the product locally on your machine, so if Jen gives it the :thumbs-up-left:  then we can use that."
